{"_id":"289ebea0-0f82-11ec-89e2-71c6940e3f6b","postId":"2020_06_a-new-pattern-for-exception-logging-727f531a-2b21-3b7a-ba16-032c960fc67a","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2020/06/a-new-pattern-for-exception-logging.html","replyTo":"3baca660-0910-11ec-b01e-757f10d01bf8","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"The point of \"logging scope\" data is that it's values that are often useful when debugging. One common example is a user id. The fact that the \"apply user id middleware\" is in the call stack only tells you that a user has been logged in; it doesn't tell you *which* user was logged in.","date":"2021-09-07T02:20:24.448Z"}